result.execSummary:
The defendant Tyler Steward was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 1st-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample; pay DNA surcharge; payable from defendant's prison funds at a percentage to be determined by the Dept. of Corrections (DOC). Remainder to be paid during the period of extended supervision. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. Court WAIVED COSTS/FEES due to indigency. Cash bail applied.
- Restitution set at ZERO.

superMiscConds.notes: - Obtain/maintain full-time employment of full-time enrollment in school, or combination of both.
- NO CONTACT ORDER with Malachi O.

- Mental Health Evaluation; comply with recommended treatment and take all prescribed medications.
- Trauma Therapy and counseling programs, as determined by DOC Agent.
- AODA assessment; comply with recommended treatment.

supervisions.notes: Court advised defendant that he is prohibited from firearm possession, ammunition or body armor. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote until his civil rights are restored.

Sentencing proceeded. Court reviewed Character Reference Letters. State complied with Victim Notification. Statements by the State, Defense, and Defendant. Exhibit 1; Received.

AS TO AMENDED COUNT 1:  
Court sentenced the Defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of FOUR (4) YEARS, with credit for 45 DAYS time served. 
The term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is TWO (2) YEARS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is TWO (2) YEARS.  

Court found Defendant IS ELIGIBLE for the Challenge Incarceration Program. 
Court found Defendant IS ELIGIBLE for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program. 
 
CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- AODA Assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
- Mental Health Evaluation, comply with recommended treatment and take all prescribed medications.
-Trauma Therapy and counseling programs, as determined by DOC Agent. 
- Obtain/Maintain Full-Time Employment or Full-Time Enrollment in School, or combination of both.
- No Contact Order with Malachi O.

Court set Restitution at ZERO.  

Court ordered Defendant to provide a DNA SAMPLE and pay DNA SURCHARGE, payable from Defendant's prison funds at a percentage to be determined by the Department of Corrections (DOC). Remainder to be paid during the period of Extended Supervision. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.CASH BAIL WILL APPLY.

Court WAIVED COSTS/FEES due to Indigency. 

Court advised Defendant that he is prohibited from firearm possession, ammunition or body armor. 
Court advised Defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote until his civil rights are restored. 
Court advised Defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.

FILED: Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief and Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence.

Defendant Tyler Steward in court with attorney Arial Jade Rosenberg.  Joshua Miles Mathy appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Case in Court for Plea/Sentencing hearing. Discussion placed on the record. Parties have reached a resolution in this matter. State complied with Victim Notification. Plea hearing proceeded. Negotiations placed on the record, and confirmed by Defense and Defendant. 

STATE FILED AN AMENDED INFORMATION. Defense waived reading of the Amended Information, and temporarily entered a plea of Not Guilty on behalf of Defendant.

AS TO AMENDED COUNT 1: 
Defendant changed his plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to the plea, and advised of Constitutional Rights and maximum penalties. Defendant advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found Defendant knowingly, voluntarily, and intelligently waived all his rights. Parties stipulated to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis for the plea. Court found Defendant GUILTY as charged in the Amended Information, and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction. 

Court advised Defendant that he is prohibited from firearm possession, ammunition, or body armor. 
Court advised Defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and he may not vote until his civil rights are restored. 

FILED: Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum, and Elements of the Offense/Jury Instructions.
